div.div:
More direct methods can just apply one interface such as information rather than applying derivation methods or general differences to create similarities.
A graph where these variables/similarities are always positioned or adjacently positioned to make these queries trivial would be a generally useful graph, like a graph where the useful sequences of these similarities are always arranged in those sequences.
However, some queries like iteration/abstract queries will involve differences that will make different graph positioning functions useful, so a 'generally useful graph to make all solution automation workflows trivial' is non-trivial and more useful.
The above graph represents one workflow (like 'standardize, abstract, specify').
Another workflow would connect different bases/standards/similarities, such as 'connect problems to cross solutions on the way to problems' or 'connect solutions to find variables of solutions'.
